<div id="review_2030133411" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2030133411" />
    <a title="Lisa" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/67178094-lisa"><img alt="Lisa" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1492991826p2/67178094.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2030133411?book_show_action=true">Jun 15, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lisa" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lisa" href="/user/show/67178094-lisa">Lisa</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/29229694-the-rotherham-trunk-murder">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2030133411" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16969154589545259799"><strong>MAY include spoilers</strong><br/><br/>Excellent Writing and Research!<br/>&quot;The fact that, since the murder, Ambrose had uttered the words “Irene cry” is surely proof that Ambrose was present when Irene was killed&quot;<br/><br/>I love reading this author&apos;s books, and seeing her come up with her theories - but comments like this, using words like SURELY, or we MUST ASSUME just don&apos;t sit well with me.<br/><br/>No it isn&apos;t proof. It could be something Avice communicated to him, something she told him to say. The author stated in her book that &quot;s</span>
  <span id="freeText16969154589545259799" style="display:none"><strong>MAY include spoilers</strong><br /><br />Excellent Writing and Research!<br />"The fact that, since the murder, Ambrose had uttered the words “Irene cry” is surely proof that Ambrose was present when Irene was killed"<br /><br />I love reading this author's books, and seeing her come up with her theories - but comments like this, using words like SURELY, or we MUST ASSUME just don't sit well with me.<br /><br />No it isn't proof. It could be something Avice communicated to him, something she told him to say. The author stated in her book that "surely" Avice learned to commuicate with Ambrose, and part of her theory was to make Ambrose understand that the doctors needed him to believe he was incapable of doing certain things...so why is it a far stretch to believe she taught him to say this as well?<br /><br />She also says: "Bagley says that she should tell the police that she hadn’t seen him for some considerable time and that she found him sitting in the kitchen paying a surprise visit when she came back from shopping." <br /><br />This is not going to work because she will be caught in this lie. Walter will be questioned separately, and suspicion will fall on Avice when it's found that she's lied and "tried" to throw blame on someone they cannot find.<br /><br />Since they have semen stains, why isn't anyone (police OR author's theory) contributing them to consensual sex with the perverted uncle/bf? Surely there have been chances for them to sneak into her room for trysts. <br /><br />The author does not provide in her theory for the suspicious person who visited Irene, either (the one who could only be seen from the waist down) for about 30 minutes on the day she was murdered. We still do not know who that was for sure. How do we know THAT was not the murderer, and that whoever it was, was so close to her (&amp; the family) or had been there so many times, that they knew about the hiding spots, how to get into her room, and about the attic? It could have been someone she spent a lot of time with and told her secrets to (such as pervert bf/uncle. And he was strong, young and healthy enough not to need help hiding the body. <br /><br />Even if it wasn't him, IRENE would have opened her door herself, and ... in just about every house, there is an attic in the bedroom closet. The tin box was just a bonus when he got up there.<br /><br />In this case, maybe during a struggle, she was able to get a little ways out of the room, and Ambrose saw her crying, which would explain his comment.<br /><br />The author seems convinced that a plan was made between Avice and her father to cover for Ambrose. There could have been, but there just isn't enough evidence of that for me. We aren't privy to any of the very good answers that are left open, that the Author asks. The ones that are contradictory between Avice and Walters statements. The police should have picked up on those and dug deeper. </span>
  <a data-text-id="16969154589545259799" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


